Sepultwram.-The eleventh canon of Archbishop Comyn’s Synod‚ prohibite, under the pain of an anathema, any person to bury in a churchyud, unless he can shew by an authentic writing, or by undeniable evidence, that it was consecrated by a bishop‚ not only as a sanctuar-y and place of refuge, but also for a place of sepulture; and that no laymen shall presume to bury their dead in such consecrated place without the presence of a priest.—Harris’s Ware’s Bislwps, p. 3 16.

In 1427, John, the sixth Earl of Kildara was buried in this monastery3 and in 147 8, his son and successor Thomas, the seventh Earl, was buried with him (Archdall’s Lodge, vol. i. p. 82). It is possible that the Fitz-Gerald monument, now in the outside wall of St. Werburye’s church‚ Dublin, may have been the monument of one of these earls3 and that at the desecration of the priory chapel‚ it may have been removed to that church‚ by the piety of his representative&
